{
  "response": "# E-Commerce Product Grid Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, users relying on zoom, users who cannot rely on color-only state cues  \n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation  \n\n**Feature:** Accessible e-commerce product listing page with product cards, sorting, filters, two-handle price range slider, cart feedback, cart badge update, and pagination.  \n**Risk Level:** Medium  \n**Component/Page Type:** Product listing page, product card list, form controls, disclosure/filter panel, custom slider, pagination, live status feedback  \n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis plan covers the accessibility design for an outdoor gear retailer product listing page showing 24 products per page out of 847 total products. The page includes product cards, sorting, filters, a custom two-handle price range slider, add-to-cart confirmation, header cart count updates, and pagination.\n\nThe existing implementation has several accessibility risks:\n\n- Product cards are clickable `<div>` elements instead of semantic links/buttons.\n- Star ratings use Unicode stars with no screen reader equivalent.\n- Sale prices rely on visual strikethrough without spoken context.\n- Add-to-cart feedback and cart badge changes are silent.\n- The price range slider is custom and lacks ARIA.\n- The filter panel changes visibility and state.\n- Toast notification appears outside the main landmark.\n\nThis plan is not claiming the whole e-commerce site is accessible. It covers the product listing page and the scoped interactions named above. Global navigation, checkout, authentication, search autocomplete, and account flows need separate plans if they contain additional interaction patterns.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe page should use native semantic structure wherever possible. Product cards must be list items, not a data table, because the content is a collection of products rather than tabular relationships. This satisfies WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships and WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n\n### Page Landmarks\n\n- Header: contains site navigation and cart link/button.\n- Main: contains the product listing page content.\n- Filter region: use a named `<section>` or `<aside>` within main, depending on layout.\n- Product results section: contains result count, sort control, product list, and pagination.\n- Pagination nav: use `<nav aria-label=\"Product pagination\">`.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships: landmarks and semantic grouping expose structure.\n- WCAG 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks: provide skip link to main content.\n- WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels: headings and labels describe topic and purpose.\n\n### Heading Hierarchy\n\nRecommended structure:\n\n- `<h1>`: \u201cOutdoor Gear\u201d\n- `<h2>`: \u201cFilters\u201d\n- `<h2>`: \u201cProducts\u201d\n- Product card names: `<h3>` inside each list item, because product cards sit under the Products section.\n- If the page has no \u201cProducts\u201d section heading, product names may be `<h2>`, but avoid skipping heading levels.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<body>\n  <a href=\"#main-content\" class=\"skip-link\">Skip to main content</a>\n\n  <header>\n    <nav aria-label=\"Primary navigation\">...</nav>\n    <a href=\"/cart\" aria-label=\"Cart, 3 items\">\n      Cart <span aria-hidden=\"true\">3</span>\n    </a>\n  </header>\n\n  <main id=\"main-content\">\n    <h1>Outdoor Gear</h1>\n\n    <section aria-labelledby=\"filters-heading\">\n      <h2 id=\"filters-heading\">Filters</h2>\n      <!-- mobile disclosure button + filter form -->\n    </section>\n\n    <section aria-labelledby=\"products-heading\">\n      <h2 id=\"products-heading\">Products</h2>\n\n      <p id=\"results-count\">847 products</p>\n\n      <form aria-label=\"Sort products\">\n        <label for=\"sort-products\">Sort by</label>\n        <select id=\"sort-products\" name=\"sort\">\n          <option>Best Match</option>\n          <option>Price: Low to High</option>\n          <option>Price: High to Low</option>\n          <option>Customer Rating</option>\n        </select>\n      </form>\n\n      <ul role=\"list\" aria-describedby=\"results-count\">\n        <li>\n          <article aria-labelledby=\"product-seaborn-down-jacket\">\n            <h3 id=\"product-seaborn-down-jacket\">\n              <a href=\"/products/seaborn-down-jacket\">Seaborn Down Jacket</a>\n            </h3>\n            <!-- image, rating, price, availability, button -->\n          </article>\n        </li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <nav aria-label=\"Product pagination\">...</nav>\n    </section>\n\n    <div aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\" id=\"cart-feedback\"></div>\n  </main>\n</body>\n```\n\nThe cart feedback live region should exist in the DOM before add-to-cart actions occur. Do not attach `aria-live` only to the toast that appears after the action, because dynamically inserted live regions are not reliably announced. WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Product name link | Native link | Tab focuses link; Enter opens product detail | Native `<a href>`; no click handler on card container | 2.1.1, 2.4.4, 4.1.2 |\n| Add to Cart button | APG Button pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab focuses; Enter/Space activates | Native `<button>`; `disabled` when unavailable | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Sort control | Native select | Tab focuses; arrow keys change option per browser; Enter/Space opens in some UAs | Visible `<label>`; selected `<option>` communicates current value | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Mobile filter panel toggle | APG Disclosure pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/ | Tab focuses; Enter/Space expands/collapses | `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Filter checkboxes | Native checkbox groups | Tab through controls; Space toggles | `<fieldset>`, `<legend>`, native checked state | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Two-handle price slider | APG Slider pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/slider/ | Tab to each handle; arrows adjust; Page Up/Down larger step; Home/End min/max | `role=\"slider\"`, `aria-valuemin`, `aria-valuemax`, `aria-valuenow`, `aria-valuetext`, accessible name | 2.1.1, 2.5.7, 4.1.2 |\n| Pagination links/buttons | Native links/buttons; pagination nav | Tab through pages; Enter activates | `aria-current=\"page\"` on current page; nav label | 2.1.1, 2.4.4, 2.4.7, 4.1.2 |\n| Toast \u201cView Cart\u201d link | Native link inside visual toast | Tab reaches link if toast remains visible long enough; Enter opens cart | Descriptive link text; no live region only on toast | 2.1.1, 2.4.4, 4.1.3 |\n| Header cart link/button | Native link/button | Tab focuses; Enter opens cart | `aria-label=\"Cart, N items\"` updates after add | 2.4.4, 4.1.2 |\n\n### Product Card Interaction\n\nThe card container must not be the only clickable target. The product name should be the link. If the design requires the full card to be clickable, implement that without creating nested interactive controls or stealing focus from the Add to Cart button. The safest pattern is a normal product name link plus normal button controls.\n\nExpected screen reader behavior:\n\n- Product name announces as a link.\n- Rating announces once as \u201c4 out of 5 stars.\u201d\n- Sale price announces as \u201cWas $149, now $89.\u201d\n- Availability announces as text, such as \u201cLow stock.\u201d\n- Add to Cart announces as a button.\n\n### Sort Control\n\nUse a native `<select>` with visible label \u201cSort by.\u201d The selected option communicates the current sort. If changing the sort reloads results automatically, announce the updated result state in a polite status region, such as \u201cProducts sorted by Price: Low to High.\u201d\n\nDo not use an unlabeled custom dropdown unless there is a strong product requirement. A native select is more robust across NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, and keyboard users.\n\n### Filter Panel\n\nDesktop filters may be persistently visible. Mobile filters should use APG Disclosure:\n\n- Button text: \u201cFilters\u201d\n- `aria-expanded=\"false\"` when collapsed\n- `aria-expanded=\"true\"` when expanded\n- `aria-controls=\"product-filters-panel\"`\n\nInside the filter panel:\n\n- Category, Brand, Color: each group uses `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`.\n- Individual filters use native checkboxes with visible labels.\n- Price Range uses a named group and two slider handles.\n\n### Price Range Slider\n\nThe custom third-party slider must expose two separate slider handles:\n\n- Minimum price handle:\n  - Accessible name: \u201cMinimum price\u201d\n  - `role=\"slider\"`\n  - `aria-valuemin=\"0\"`\n  - `aria-valuemax` equal to the current maximum handle value\n  - `aria-valuenow` equal to current minimum\n  - `aria-valuetext=\"Minimum price: $25\"`\n\n- Maximum price handle:\n  - Accessible name: \u201cMaximum price\u201d\n  - `role=\"slider\"`\n  - `aria-valuemin` equal to current minimum handle value\n  - `aria-valuemax=\"500\"` or configured max\n  - `aria-valuenow` equal to current maximum\n  - `aria-valuetext=\"Maximum price: $250\"`\n\nKeyboard model:\n\n- Left/Down Arrow: decrease focused handle by one step.\n- Right/Up Arrow: increase focused handle by one step.\n- Page Down: decrease by larger step.\n- Page Up: increase by larger step.\n- Home: move to minimum allowed value.\n- End: move to maximum allowed value.\n- Handles must not cross; programmatic min/max must update accordingly.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard: slider must be operable by keyboard.\n- WCAG 2.5.7 Dragging Movements: dragging must have keyboard/single-pointer alternatives.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value: slider role and values must be exposed.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\nLogical tab order:\n\n1. Skip link\n2. Header navigation\n3. Cart link/button\n4. Main heading area\n5. Mobile filter disclosure button, if present\n6. Filter controls in visual order when expanded or visible\n7. Sort select\n8. Product links and Add to Cart buttons in DOM order\n9. Pagination controls\n\nFocus should follow visual reading order per WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Filter Disclosure Focus\n\nWhen the mobile filter panel opens, focus should remain on the disclosure button unless the user explicitly tabs into the panel. This matches the APG Disclosure pattern and avoids unexpected focus jumps. When it closes, focus remains on the button.\n\nCollapsed filter content must not remain keyboard-focusable. Use conditional rendering or `hidden`. If the panel is visually offscreen, also ensure it is not reachable by keyboard. Do not use `aria-hidden=\"true\"` alone on focusable content.\n\n### Add to Cart Focus\n\nWhen Add to Cart is activated:\n\n- Focus remains on the Add to Cart button.\n- Button label changes to \u201cAdded\u201d or \u201cAdded to cart\u201d for 3 seconds.\n- A pre-existing polite live region receives: \u201cSeaborn Down Jacket added to cart.\u201d\n- The visual toast appears and includes \u201cView Cart\u201d as a normal link.\n- Do not move focus to the toast automatically. Moving focus would interrupt browsing flow across 24 products.\n\nAfter 3 seconds:\n\n- Button label returns to \u201cAdd to Cart\u201d unless product quantity state requires another persistent label.\n- Screen reader users should not receive another unnecessary announcement when the temporary label resets.\n\n### Pagination Focus\n\nWhen changing pages:\n\n- If navigation causes a route change, browser/page focus handling should move to the page\u2019s `<h1>` or the results heading.\n- If updating results client-side, focus should move to the Products heading or results count with `tabindex=\"-1\"` after update, and the status region should announce \u201cPage 2 loaded, showing products 25 to 48 of 847.\u201d\n- Current page uses `aria-current=\"page\"`.\n\n### Focus Indicators\n\nAll interactive controls require visible focus indicators meeting WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible and WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance. Use a two-color focus ring where possible so the indicator remains visible against product images, light backgrounds, and dark UI.\n\nTargets should be at least 24x24 CSS pixels, with 44x44 recommended for add-to-cart, pagination, filter toggles, and slider handles. WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Filter panel collapsed/expanded | Panel hidden/visible; chevron icon | Disclosure button state | `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 4.1.2 |\n| Checkbox unchecked/checked | Checkmark and label | Native checkbox state | Native `checked` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Price slider value | Handle position and visible price text | Slider role/value | `role=\"slider\"`, `aria-valuenow`, `aria-valuetext` | 4.1.2 |\n| Sort selected | Selected option visible | Native select value | Selected `<option>` | 4.1.2 |\n| Product rating | Stars visual | Spoken equivalent | `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on stars; screen-reader text | 1.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Sale price | Sale badge, strikethrough original price, sale price | Spoken sequence \u201cWas X, now Y\u201d | `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on visual strikethrough; SR-only text | 1.3.1 |\n| Availability | Text badge \u201cIn Stock,\u201d \u201cLow Stock,\u201d \u201cOut of Stock\u201d | Text content | No ARIA needed if text is present | 1.4.1, 1.3.1 |\n| Add to cart success | Button label changes; toast appears | Pre-existing live region message | `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Cart count | Badge count increments | Cart accessible name updates | `aria-label=\"Cart, N items\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Current page | Current page visually highlighted | Current page identified | `aria-current=\"page\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Out of stock button | Button disabled or replaced with unavailable text | Native disabled state | `disabled` on native button | 4.1.2 |\n\n### Star Rating Pattern\n\nVisual Unicode stars should not be exposed directly to assistive technology. Some screen readers announce them as repeated characters, which is noisy and unclear.\n\nRequired pattern:\n\n```html\n<span aria-label=\"4 out of 5 stars\">\n  <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2606</span>\n</span>\n```\n\nIf using icon fonts instead of text stars:\n\n- Decorative icon elements must be `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n- The parent rating element provides the accessible equivalent.\n- Include rating count if available, such as \u201c4 out of 5 stars, 128 reviews.\u201d\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content: non-text star representation needs text alternative.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value: accessible name must communicate the value.\n\n### Sale Price Pattern\n\nDo not rely on `<del>` or `<s>` being announced correctly. Some AT may announce \u201cdeleted,\u201d which does not provide purchase context.\n\nRequired spoken pattern:\n\n```html\n<span class=\"price\">\n  <s aria-hidden=\"true\">$149</s>\n  <span class=\"sr-only\">Was $149, now </span>\n  <span>$89</span>\n</span>\n```\n\nThe visible sale badge \u201cSale\u201d may remain visible. If the badge is only decorative and the price text already communicates sale context, avoid duplicate announcements. If it conveys meaningful state, expose it once in the product card.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships: price relationship must be available programmatically.\n- WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color: sale cannot rely on red alone.\n\n### Add to Cart Feedback\n\nUse one pre-existing live region for cart action feedback:\n\n```html\n<div id=\"cart-feedback\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n```\n\nOn add:\n\n- Write \u201cSeaborn Down Jacket added to cart.\u201d\n- Show the visual toast with \u201cSeaborn Down Jacket added to cart. View Cart.\u201d\n- Update cart link accessible name to \u201cCart, 4 items.\u201d\n- Keep focus on the Add to Cart button.\n\nDo not create one live region per product card. Do not put `role=\"alert\"` inside the product card loop. Do not make the cart badge a live region for every increment; it risks becoming chatty. The live region announces the completed action, while the cart link\u2019s accessible name provides current state on focus.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages: cart action confirmation must be announced without moving focus.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value: cart link name must reflect count.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\nText and UI contrast must meet WCAG 2.2 AA:\n\n- Normal text: 4.5:1 minimum.\n- Large text: 3:1 minimum.\n- UI controls, focus indicators, slider handles, badges: 3:1 minimum against adjacent colors.\n\nAvailability and sale states must not rely on color alone:\n\n- \u201cLow Stock\u201d must be visible text, not only orange/red color.\n- \u201cOut of Stock\u201d must be visible text and button disabled/unavailable.\n- Sale state should include visible \u201cSale\u201d text and price context, not only red price.\n- Filter selected state should use checkbox state plus label, not only color.\n\nResponsive and zoom requirements:\n\n- Product grid must reflow at 200% zoom and 400% zoom without horizontal scrolling at 320px equivalent width.\n- Product cards should remain readable in a single column at narrow widths.\n- Filter panel must remain operable on mobile and high zoom.\n- Sticky headers must not obscure focused controls. WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured.\n\nMotion:\n\n- Toast entrance/exit animation must respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.\n- No essential information should depend on animation timing.\n- The 3-second button label reset is acceptable only because the live region confirmation persists conceptually through the action; the user does not need to perceive the temporary visual state to complete the task.\n\nTouch targets:\n\n- Add to Cart, filter toggle, checkbox labels, pagination controls, and slider handles should be at least 44x44 CSS pixels where feasible.\n- Minimum WCAG 2.5.8 target size is 24x24 CSS pixels.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n### Product Images\n\n- Product images need meaningful alt text if they help identify the product.\n- Recommended format: `alt=\"Seaborn Down Jacket in navy blue\"`.\n- If the image is adjacent to an identical product name link and adds no new information, empty alt may be acceptable. For shopping, product appearance is often meaningful, so default to concise descriptive alt.\n\nWCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content.\n\n### Product Links\n\nProduct name links must be descriptive on their own:\n\n- Good: \u201cSeaborn Down Jacket\u201d\n- Avoid: \u201cView product\u201d repeated 24 times without context.\n\nWCAG 2.4.4 Link Purpose.\n\n### Filter Labels\n\nEvery checkbox must have a visible label. Category, Brand, Color, and Price Range groups must have legends or accessible group names.\n\nExamples:\n\n- `<legend>Category</legend>`\n- `<legend>Brand</legend>`\n- `<legend>Color</legend>`\n- `<legend>Price range</legend>`\n\nWCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships and WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n### Toast Content\n\nToast text should be specific:\n\n- \u201cSeaborn Down Jacket added to cart. View Cart\u201d\n- \u201cView Cart\u201d is descriptive enough in this context.\n- If multiple toasts stack, avoid repeating live announcements for all visible toasts. The live region should announce only the newest cart action.\n\n### Reading Order\n\nDOM order should match visual order:\n\n1. Product image\n2. Product name\n3. Rating\n4. Price\n5. Availability\n6. Add to Cart\n\nDo not visually reorder card content with CSS in a way that changes meaning. WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated Testing\n\nRun axe-core on these states:\n\n- Default product listing page.\n- Mobile filter collapsed.\n- Mobile filter expanded.\n- Product with sale price.\n- Product out of stock.\n- Product after Add to Cart action.\n- Pagination current page state.\n- Price slider at default, changed, min, and max values.\n\nExpected axe coverage:\n\n- Missing labels.\n- Invalid ARIA attributes.\n- Landmark structure.\n- Color contrast.\n- Form control names.\n- `aria-current` validity.\n\nAxe will not fully verify:\n\n- Live region announcement reliability.\n- Whether the star rating spoken text is understandable.\n- Focus order quality.\n- Slider keyboard behavior.\n- Whether sale price sounds correct in real AT.\n\n### Static Analysis\n\nFor React/Next.js, use eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y as a CI gate.\n\nWatch for:\n\n- Click handlers on non-interactive elements.\n- Missing alt text.\n- Invalid ARIA props.\n- Label-control association.\n- Custom controls without keyboard handlers.\n\nKnown false positives may occur around custom components that pass props through. Confirm rendered DOM.\n\n### Manual Keyboard Testing\n\nTest with real keyboard input:\n\n- Tab from top of page through header, filters, sort, products, add-to-cart buttons, and pagination.\n- Shift+Tab reverses logically.\n- Mobile filter button opens/closes with Enter and Space.\n- Checkbox filters toggle with Space.\n- Sort select is operable with keyboard.\n- Price slider handles can be reached and adjusted using arrows, Page Up/Down, Home, and End.\n- Add to Cart works with Enter and Space.\n- Toast View Cart link is keyboard reachable if visible.\n- Pagination works with Enter.\n- Focus indicators remain visible at normal zoom, 200% zoom, and narrow viewport.\n\n### Screen Reader Testing\n\nUse NVDA + Firefox/Chrome, JAWS + Chrome/Edge, and VoiceOver + Safari.\n\nScenarios:\n\n- Navigate by landmarks: header, main, filter section, product section, pagination.\n- Navigate headings: page heading, Filters, Products, product names.\n- Product card reading: product name, image alt, rating, sale price, availability, button.\n- Verify rating announces once as \u201c4 out of 5 stars,\u201d not \u201cstar star star.\u201d\n- Verify sale price announces \u201cWas $149, now $89.\u201d\n- Activate Add to Cart and confirm live region announces product added.\n- Focus cart link and confirm it announces updated count: \u201cCart, 4 items.\u201d\n- Change price slider and verify value text includes formatted dollars.\n- Navigate pagination and confirm current page is announced.\n\n### DOM Verification\n\nRequired DOM checks:\n\n- Product list renders as `<ul>` with `<li>` children.\n- Product card name is a heading containing a real link.\n- Visual star characters/icons have `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n- Rating has a single accessible text equivalent.\n- Visual strikethrough price has `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n- SR-only sale text exists before the sale price.\n- Filter groups use `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`.\n- Price slider handles contain correct role, name, min, max, now, and value text.\n- Cart feedback live region exists before add-to-cart action.\n- Cart link `aria-label` updates after cart count changes.\n- Current pagination page has `aria-current=\"page\"`.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Product List and Product Card Semantics\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Product listing page component\n- Product card component\n- Product card tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<section aria-labelledby=\"products-heading\">\n  <h2 id=\"products-heading\">Products</h2>\n  <p id=\"results-count\">847 products</p>\n  <ul role=\"list\" aria-describedby=\"results-count\">\n    <li>\n      <article aria-labelledby=\"product-id-title\">\n        <img alt=\"Product description\">\n        <h3 id=\"product-id-title\">\n          <a href=\"/products/product-slug\">Product name</a>\n        </h3>\n      </article>\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n</section>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-describedby` on product list references result count. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `aria-labelledby` on article may reference product heading. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- Avoid ARIA when native semantics are sufficient.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab focuses product links and Add to Cart buttons.\n- Enter opens product links.\n- No click-only card behavior.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Product list is `<ul>/<li>`.\n- Product title is a heading and link.\n- No clickable `<div>` replaces native link/button.\n- Tab order enters product controls in visual order.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.4 Link Purpose\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify card semantics, link/button separation, heading level, and DOM order.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Rating, Sale Price, and Availability States\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Product rating component\n- Product price component\n- Availability badge component\n- Unit and DOM tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<span aria-label=\"4 out of 5 stars\">\n  <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2606</span>\n</span>\n\n<span>\n  <s aria-hidden=\"true\">$149</s>\n  <span class=\"sr-only\">Was $149, now </span>\n  <span>$89</span>\n</span>\n\n<span>Low Stock</span>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on decorative stars/icons. WCAG 1.1.1.\n- Rating accessible name communicates numeric value. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on visual strikethrough original price. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- No ARIA needed for availability if visible text communicates status.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- None unless rating or price is interactive, which is not in scope.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Screen reader equivalent exists for rating.\n- Visual stars are hidden from accessibility tree.\n- Sale price includes \u201cWas X, now Y\u201d in accessible text.\n- Low stock/out of stock states include visible text, not color alone.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.1.1 Non-text Content\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 1.4.1 Use of Color\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify rating and sale price are not noisy or misleading in screen reader output.\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Sort and Filter Controls\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Sort control component\n- Filter panel component\n- Filter group components\n- Tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<label for=\"sort-products\">Sort by</label>\n<select id=\"sort-products\" name=\"sort\">\n  <option>Best Match</option>\n</select>\n\n<button aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"product-filters-panel\">\n  Filters\n</button>\n\n<div id=\"product-filters-panel\">\n  <fieldset>\n    <legend>Category</legend>\n    <label><input type=\"checkbox\" name=\"category\" value=\"jackets\"> Jackets</label>\n  </fieldset>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-expanded` on mobile filter toggle. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls` references filter panel. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Native checkbox checked state. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Sort select follows native keyboard behavior.\n- Filter toggle opens/closes with Enter and Space.\n- Checkboxes toggle with Space.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Sort has visible label.\n- Filter groups use fieldset/legend.\n- Mobile filter collapsed state removes controls from tab order.\n- `aria-expanded` matches visual state.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.6 Headings and Labels\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify filter disclosure and grouped controls match APG/native patterns.\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Two-Handle Price Range Slider\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Price range slider wrapper around third-party component\n- Slider keyboard tests\n- Rendered DOM tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div role=\"group\" aria-labelledby=\"price-range-label\">\n  <span id=\"price-range-label\">Price range</span>\n\n  <div\n    role=\"slider\"\n    aria-label=\"Minimum price\"\n    aria-valuemin=\"0\"\n    aria-valuemax=\"250\"\n    aria-valuenow=\"25\"\n    aria-valuetext=\"Minimum price: $25\"\n    tabindex=\"0\">\n  </div>\n\n  <div\n    role=\"slider\"\n    aria-label=\"Maximum price\"\n    aria-valuemin=\"25\"\n    aria-valuemax=\"500\"\n    aria-valuenow=\"250\"\n    aria-valuetext=\"Maximum price: $250\"\n    tabindex=\"0\">\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `role=\"slider\"` on each handle. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby` for each handle. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-valuemin`, `aria-valuemax`, `aria-valuenow`. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-valuetext` with formatted price. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Arrow keys adjust focused handle.\n- Page Up/Down adjusts by larger step.\n- Home/End moves to allowed bounds.\n- Minimum and maximum handles cannot cross.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Each handle is tabbable.\n- Values update after keyboard interaction.\n- `aria-valuetext` updates with formatted dollars.\n- Dragging is not the only way to change price range.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.5.7 Dragging Movements\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify third-party slider wrapper exposes complete slider semantics and keyboard support.\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Add to Cart Feedback, Toast, and Cart Badge\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Add to Cart button component\n- Cart feedback live region\n- Header cart link/button\n- Toast component\n- Interaction tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<button type=\"button\">Add to Cart</button>\n\n<div id=\"cart-feedback\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n\n<a href=\"/cart\" aria-label=\"Cart, 4 items\">\n  Cart <span aria-hidden=\"true\">4</span>\n</a>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-live=\"polite\"` for pre-existing cart action feedback region. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-atomic=\"true\"` so complete message is announced. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- Cart link `aria-label=\"Cart, N items\"`. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Native `disabled` for out-of-stock button state. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Add to Cart activates with Enter and Space.\n- Focus remains on the button.\n- Toast View Cart link is reachable if toast remains interactive.\n- Cart link opens cart with Enter.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Add to Cart writes message to pre-existing live region.\n- Button label changes to \u201cAdded\u201d for 3 seconds.\n- Cart link accessible name updates with new count.\n- Out-of-stock products cannot be added and expose disabled state.\n- No repeated live regions exist inside the product card loop.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify the action confirmation is announced without focus theft and cart count is exposed without chatty badge announcements.\n\n---\n\n### Task 6: Pagination\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Pagination component\n- Pagination tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<nav aria-label=\"Product pagination\">\n  <a href=\"?page=1\">Previous</a>\n  <a href=\"?page=1\">1</a>\n  <a href=\"?page=2\" aria-current=\"page\">2</a>\n  <a href=\"?page=3\">3</a>\n  <a href=\"?page=3\">Next</a>\n</nav>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-label=\"Product pagination\"` on nav. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `aria-current=\"page\"` on current page. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab reaches pagination links.\n- Enter activates links.\n- Disabled Previous/Next should be removed, disabled with native button semantics, or rendered as non-interactive text.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Current page is programmatically identified.\n- Pagination nav has accessible name.\n- Page change updates focus/status appropriately for SPA transitions.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.4 Link Purpose\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify current page state, focus behavior after page change, and accessible pagination names.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Product card semantics | `<ul>/<li>`, heading level, product link, no clickable div-only cards |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Rating/price/status | Star rating announcement, sale price context, color-independent availability |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Sort/filter | Visible labels, fieldset/legend, mobile disclosure state |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Price slider | APG slider semantics, keyboard support, value text |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Cart feedback | Pre-existing live region, focus retention, cart label update |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 6 | Pagination | Landmark label, `aria-current`, SPA focus/status behavior |\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\nThe page consists of six accessibility-critical component groups:\n\n1. Product list and product cards using native list, article, heading, link, image, and button semantics.\n2. Sort and filter controls using native select, disclosure, checkbox groups, and fieldsets.\n3. A custom two-handle price range slider following the APG Slider pattern.\n4. Rating, price, sale, and availability display components with accessible text equivalents.\n5. Add-to-cart feedback using a pre-existing polite live region and cart link accessible name updates.\n6. Pagination using a named navigation landmark and `aria-current`.\n\nPrimary APG patterns:\n\n- Button\n- Disclosure\n- Slider\n\nNative HTML patterns are preferred for links, selects, checkboxes, forms, and pagination links.\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes\n\nThis plan prevents these likely defects:\n\n- Product cards that are clickable only by mouse.\n- Product names that are not real links.\n- Unicode stars being read as repeated symbols.\n- Sale prices being announced as \u201cdeleted\u201d or lacking \u201cwas/now\u201d context.\n- Low stock indicated only by color.\n- Filter controls lacking group labels.\n- Collapsed mobile filters remaining in the tab order.\n- Custom price slider being unusable by keyboard.\n- Add-to-cart confirmation appearing visually but not being announced.\n- Toast live region not being announced because it was inserted too late.\n- Cart badge count changing silently.\n- Pagination current page being visual only.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/\n- APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- APG Disclosure Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/\n- APG Slider Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/slider/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- a11y-critic skill: for post-plan and post-implementation review",
